    <dl class="portalMessage info" id="kssPortalMessage" style="display:none"><dt>Info</dt>
        <dd></dd>
    </dl><div id="content">

                            

                            

                             <div id="viewlet-above-content-title"></div>
                             
                                 
                                 
            
                <h1 id="parent-fieldname-title" class="documentFirstHeading">
                    Home
                </h1>
            
            
        
                             
                             <div id="viewlet-below-content-title">
</div>

                             
                                 
                                 
            
                
            
            
        
                             

                             <div id="viewlet-above-content-body">

</div>
                             <div id="content-core">
                                 
    
        
        <div class="" id="parent-fieldname-text-d02609a6384767d16acaf1febea4fb7f">
            
<p><img class="image-right" alt="Combustion and Engines" title="Combustion and Engines" src="http://www.eng.ox.ac.uk/engines/images/combustion-engines.jpg/image_preview" />A combination of analytical and experimental work as well as modelling is being conducted in the Combustion &amp; Engines group. Currently the group's research interests mainly lie in the following areas:</p>
<ul><li>Generic combustion analysis and instrumentation for IC engines, notably optical techniques.</li><li><a class="internal-link" title="Gasoline Direct Injection Engines" href="http://www.eng.ox.ac.uk/engines/research/gasoline-direct-injection-engines">Gasoline Direct Injection engines</a>.</li><li><a class="internal-link" title="Measurement of Particulate Emissions from GDI Engines" href="http://www.eng.ox.ac.uk/engines/research/measurement-of-particulate-emissions-from-gdi-engines">Particulate matter emissions, and co-flow diffusion flames</a>.</li><li><a class="internal-link" title="Measuring Laminar Burning Velocities" href="http://www.eng.ox.ac.uk/engines/research/measuring-laminar-burning-velocities">Laminar burning velocity measurements</a>.</li><li>Chemiluminescence measurements.</li><li>In-cylinder/exhaust emissions measurements.</li><li>Fast-response thermocouple techniques and heat flux in IC engines.</li><li>Multi-zone modelling and simulations for spark-ignition engines.</li></ul><p><a class="internal-link" title="Gasoline Direct Injection Engines" href="http://www.eng.ox.ac.uk/engines/research/gasoline-direct-injection-engines">Gasoline Direct Injection (GDI)</a> engines enable both the output and efficiency to be improved relative to Port Fuel Injection (PFI) engines, but there is less time for mixture preparation, so it is essential to understand the fuel injection, evaporation, mixing, and combustion. We thus make extensive use of optical diagnostics, and the laser based measurements are a result of close collaboration with Prof Ewart’s group in the Clarendon Lab [link]. The downside of the reduced time for mixture preparation is a less homogeneous mixture, which in turn leads to increased emissions of particulate matter. Gasoline Direct Injection (GDI) engines can also use the injection strategy to generate mixture stratification, and this can be useful during marginal combustion conditions, such as engine warm-up. To better understand the formation of particulate matter we also take measurements of temperature, soot volume fraction and primary particle size in a co-flow diffusion flame.</p>
<p>The laminar burning velocity is of fundamental importance to combustion in engines, and our constant volume combustion vessel enables us to take measurements over wide ranging conditions of temperature, pressure, air/fuel ratio and residuals levels. Our multi-zone combustion model means we can derive the laminar burning velocity from pressure measurements, as well as making make direct measurements from schlieren images. This apparatus is also well suited to studying chemiluminescence from flames as the burn rate and optics are well-defined.</p>

            
        </div>
    
    

